			<ns0:name>mcgra...@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/109286297231979736865/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">The ARM GCC compiler likes to compute address+CONSTANT into a register so that it can then use a memory reference [basereg, -CONSTANT].  This maximizes its potential to reuse a base register given the limited range of immediate offsets (13 bits signed).

When we apply our sandboxing mask to the base register, this can truncate the address if the original address was close to the top of the sandbox region (e.g. 1G minus a little) and +CONSTANT pushes it over the top.
